In the end, what works is when you let #SEO take the backseat, lay foundations right, build great frameworks and let content grow on it, organically. Focus on business ROI and user intent, and long term, sticky, community like growth. Nothing can beat it.

Another common mistake I see folks do is taking automation and recommendation from tools very seriously, aiming for A+ scores on on-page #SEO. It's nothing but an ego massage. Feels good to see it all green but don't expect results.
#SEO works best when you measure it with long term ROI specific goals and make it work supporting other/similar channels like, content or PPC.
In essense, giving undue importance for #SEO is a mistake. Instead, what works these days are, holistic, inclusive marketing strategies that has SEO included in it, but with the right expectations.
In my experience, #SEO can rarely claim credit for business success on its own. Instead, it has to work together with other marketing teams to make sense of ROI.
The reality is that, first page ranks or second page to first page jumps look good only in #SEO reports, and are often very insignificant to businesses (generalizing here).
